{"cursor":"42520","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{infobox programming language\n| name = Ada logo = paradigm = Multi-paradigm year = 1980 designer =\n* MIL-STD-1815/Ada 83: Jean Ichbiah\n* Ada 95: Tucker Taft\n* Ada 2005: Tucker Taft\n| developer = latest_release_version = Ada 2012 latest_release_date =\n| latest_preview_version = Ada 2012 [http://www.ada-\n| auth.org/standards/ada12.html Ada 2012 Language Reference Manual]\n| latest_preview_date = \n| turing-complete = Yes typing = static, strong, safe, nominative\n| implementations = AdaCore GNAT, \nGreen Hills Software Optimising Ada 95 compiler, Atego ObjectAda,\nDDC-I Score\n| dialects = Ada 83, Ada 95, Ada 2005 influenced_by = ALGOL 68, Pascal, C++ (Ada\n| 95), Smalltalk (Ada 95), Java (Ada 2005) influenced = C++, Eiffel, PL/SQL,\n| VHDL, Ruby, Java, Seed7 operating_system = Cross-platform (multi-platform)\n| license = website = http://www.adaic.org/ file_ext = .adb .ads dialects =\n| SPARK, Ravenscar profile wikibooks = Ada Programming\n}}\n\n'Ada' is a structured, statically typed, imperative, wide-spectrum, and object-\noriented high-level computer programming language, extended from Pascal and\nother languages. It has built-in language support for explicit concurrency,\noffering tasks, synchronous message passing, protected objects, and non-\ndeterminism. Ada is an international standard; the current version (known as Ada\n2012 http://www.adaic.org/ ) is defined by ISO/IEC 8652:2012.\n\nAda was originally designed by a team led by Jean Ichbiah of CII Honeywell Bull\nunder contract to the United States Department of Defense (DoD) from 1977 to\n1983 to supersede the hundreds of programming languages then used by the DoD.\nAda was named after Ada Lovelace (1815â1852), who is credited as being the first\ncomputer programmer. J. Fuegi and J. Francis, \"Lovelace & Babbage and the\ncreation of the 1843 'notes'.\" Annals of the History of Computing 25 #4\n(OctoberâDecember 2003): 16-26. [h